<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Causes of Road Accidents | Navigator +</title>
    <%- include('partials/styles.ejs') %>
    <style>
        body { padding-top: 86px; }
        .cause-card { background: var(--card); border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: var(--radius-panel); padding: 26px; box-shadow: 0 4px 20px rgba(15,42,30,0.07); height: 100%; }
        .cause-card .badge-num { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; width: 34px; height: 34px; border-radius: 50%; background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--brand-teal), var(--brand-red)); color: white; font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; margin-right: 10px; }
        .big-stat { background: var(--card); border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: var(--radius-panel); padding: 24px; text-align: center; box-shadow: 0 4px 20px rgba(15,42,30,0.07); height: 100%; }
        .big-stat .num { font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 800; font-size: 32px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--brand-red), var(--brand-teal)); -webkit-background-clip: text; background-clip: text; color: transparent; }
        .big-stat .label { font-size: 13px; color: var(--ink-muted); }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <%- include('partials/navbar.ejs', { page: 'causes' }) %>

    <div class="page-hero text-center">
        <div class="container">
            <h1 class="display-6">Why Do Road Accidents Happen?</h1>
            <p class="mx-auto">Singapore's roads are getting more crowded — and accident numbers have been rising too. Here's what the data says is really going wrong.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="container mt-4 mb-5">

        <%- include('partials/readAloud.ejs') %>

        <div id="readable-content">
        <div class="row g-3 mb-5">
            <div class="col-6 col-md-3">
                <div class="big-stat"><div class="num">147</div><div class="label">traffic deaths in 2025, the highest in 10 years</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-6 col-md-3">
                <div class="big-stat"><div class="num">7,560</div><div class="label">injury accidents in 2025, up ~7% from 2024</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-6 col-md-3">
                <div class="big-stat"><div class="num">118,076</div><div class="label">speeding violations detected in H1 2025 alone</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-6 col-md-3">
                <div class="big-stat"><div class="num">~710</div><div class="label">PMD/PAB-related injury accidents from 2023 to Q3 2025</div></div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="row g-4 mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="cause-card">
                    <h5><span class="badge-num">1</span>Speeding</h5>
                    <p>Speeding remains one of the most common accident triggers. Higher speed means less time to react and a harder impact if something goes wrong. Speeding violations rose sharply in 2025, partly due to expanded speed cameras — though speeding-related accidents and fatalities actually fell slightly as enforcement caught up.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="cause-card">
                    <h5><span class="badge-num">2</span>Distraction</h5>
                    <p>From drivers glancing at their phones to pedestrians crossing while texting, distraction shows up again and again in Traffic Police reports. Officers describe it as "brief moments of inattention" that can prove fatal — a driver not checking for pedestrians, a rider filtering across lanes without looking, a phone screen at the worst possible second.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="cause-card">
                    <h5><span class="badge-num">3</span>Failing to keep proper control or lookout</h5>
                    <p>Many 2025 accidents were officially attributed to drivers failing to keep a proper lookout, not maintaining proper control of their vehicle, or changing lanes without due care. These are everyday lapses in attention and technique, not dramatic recklessness — which is exactly what makes them dangerous.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="cause-card">
                    <h5><span class="badge-num">4</span>Drink driving</h5>
                    <p>Drink-driving accidents have fallen in recent years, but arrests have not — meaning enforcement is catching more offenders even as the accident numbers improve. Alcohol impairs concentration, coordination, reflexes and decision-making, all of which are essential to driving safely. Singapore is lowering its legal blood-alcohol limit to bring it in line with regional peers.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="cause-card">
                    <h5><span class="badge-num">5</span>Red-light running</h5>
                    <p>Accidents caused by red-light running rose by over a third in 2025, even as the number of red-light violations detected fell — suggesting that when it happens, it's increasingly dangerous. Rushing an amber or red light removes the safety margin that traffic signals are designed to create at junctions.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="cause-card">
                    <h5><span class="badge-num">6</span>PMD and cyclist misuse</h5>
                    <p>Personal mobility devices remain a significant safety issue, especially when ridden at speed near pedestrians, without helmets, or by underage riders. Since PMDs were banned from footpaths, footpath-related PMD accidents fell by over half — but accidents on roads and cycling paths continue to occur, sometimes involving young riders who may not fully grasp traffic rules at junctions.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cause-card mb-4">
            <h5>Who's most at risk?</h5>
            <p>Elderly pedestrians and motorcyclists are disproportionately represented in Singapore's road fatalities. Although seniors make up under 13% of the population, they accounted for three-quarters of pedestrian deaths in 2025 — largely from jaywalking and needing more time to cross. Motorcyclists and pillion riders made up over half of all traffic deaths despite motorcycles being only 15% of registered vehicles, since riders have no protective structure around them in a collision.</p>
            <p class="source-note">Source: Singapore Police Force, Annual Road Traffic Situation 2025; Ministry of Transport (2025–2026)</p>
        </div>
        </div><!-- /#readable-content -->

        <div class="text-center mt-4">
            <p>Know what to do if you're ever caught in a road emergency.</p>
            <a href="/hotlines" class="btn btn-brand">See Emergency Hotlines</a>
        </div>

    </div>

    <%- include('partials/footer.ejs') %>
</body>
</html>
